@Blurhy: It's a long story. It's a really old search engine, and it was primarily made as a replacement for zerosearch.bit (which I now own the domain). The search engine isn't "proper" like modern clearnet search engines.

And yes, I'm of the opinion that search engines need to be reworked. I don't think there's actually much point in a general search engine that finds content *within* sites. Instead we should rethink how we do things.

Why bother crawling every page for videos, when you can just load up a few video site DBs? We have technology not available to clearnet search engines. So why do we try to be like them? Familiarity?

@Blurhy: Namely the ability to be able to directly access databases of merger sites. This allows us to be able to set a standard for a type of file, and then build tools around it. Want to search for news? Just grab a news merger site and fetch the merged DB from it and search through that. Want to search video? Grab a video merger site and fetch the merged DB from that.

This instantly allows us to have personalized searches, guaranteed content type, and an easy way to embed content into the search engine.

That's just one example.

@Blurhy: Sure. But ultimately you'll have to download *something* if you want to search. Again, this is part of what I mean by we need to rethink how we actually *use* search engines.

@Krixano: Don't get me wrong. I *love* merger sites. They're a wonderful tool for a specific purpose. But for a search engine? It's not so great. My idea was that a search engine would search the *merger site*. So the merger site merges the various hubs and data of a specific type, and then the search engine searches through the combined DB. 

CORS is good for *borrowing* information from other sites. Which is exactly what a search engine does. Merger sites are good for *aggregating* information. So borrowing the information from the aggregators appears to be an excellent solution, IMO.

@Krixano: They don't really do the same thing. AFAIK with CORS you can't actually touch the data from the site you're fetching from; only view it. Whereas with a merger, you can actually submit new things. They're used for different purposes.

An ideal search engine, IMO, would combine the two.

Compare: A search engine in which you must manually add each hub to the search engine itself, and as a result.
Vs: A search engine in which you only add, say, KopyKateMerger, and you automatically get data from any new hubs downloaded for KopyKateMerger, without needing to update the search engine site.

@Blurhy: Again, this is the beauty of merger sites. You don't *need* to download all of the data. You can just download the metadata and leave the rest as optional files you fetch when you want to view the whole thing. You can't do this with CORS. With CORS, you have to have the site and data that you want to view downloaded. You *could* have CORS go to a site, which isn't a merger, and that non-merger site then has optional files (how my ZeroUP search works), but it removes the automagic of getting new content that's managed by different people (preventing a dead data site).

@Krixano: Have you read the code on my site?

